You should never change any parameters coming from Genomaster because it will result in different response from you that wont be in agreement with 2 other miners that trained for 45 epochs and validators will reject your response. Simply, be patient when you don't have a job.

Not having a job can have multiple reasons:
        1) You might be a new miner.
        2) You might be a slow miner.
        3) There could be a race condition at the end of the generation phase where only a handful of jobs are left, typically given to faster miners, leaving everyone else waiting for the last jobs to finish.
        4) The GenoMaster might be busy performing an optimization step on its side.
        5) The GenoMaster might be in the process of creating a new job list.

1)  A faster miner will finish their jobs more quickly and may take over jobs from slower miners, which means more completions and more rewards. However, if you don't get a job, it generally means that the majority of miners are also not getting jobs.
 2) The GenoMaster does not dynamically assign jobs on the fly. All jobs in one generation need to be completed before the Optimizer can rank and mutate them before creating a new population.
 3) Sometimes, particularly toward the end in the worst case, all miners, including the faster ones, might have to wait for the last jobs to finish. It does not mean that everyone else is gaining more rewards while you are idle. In the majority of cases, when you are idle, 99% of others are idle too.

Hi All,
We have discovered a new architecture for the smallest model with the highest accuracy for image classification on the CIFAR-10 dataset that outperformed the state of the art. 
We did not create a new solution, but rather we were able to significantly increase the search space size for NAS due to the vast amount of compute available via miners. These results will not only showcase a better product but will allow us to publish results in scientifically community.

Just to explain what is happening here: We are searching for AI algorithms that are highly accurate for a given task but also require less compute power to run. For example, we aim to find models that, without NAS, would need a 4090 GPU to run predictions, but after applying NAS and discovering new architectures, they can operate with the same latency on much cheaper and smaller GPUs. The figure above serves as a benchmark of all those who are trying to create the best NAS algorithms that find the smallest models. What we have discovered in this subnet is a model that has only 0.06 million parameters (smaller is better) and achieves 85.5% accuracy (higher is better), surpassing the state of the art, which has 0.07 million parameters and 83% accuracy.

This is mentioned in the documentation, but I'll emphasize it again: You do not get rewarded for training a model with high accuracy. You get rewarded based on the number of jobs you complete, and you must finish them exactly as GenoMaster dictates. Otherwise, you will not reach consensus with the other three miners who have also trained the same genome, and as a result, you will be excluded from the reward distribution (and potentially blacklisted in the future). If you alter the code to achieve higher accuracy, you are actually interfering with GenoMaster's optimization decisions.

Hello, As reported yesterday, there was a set of miners that were returning results in 1 second. Sending results in one second is not illegal since if you train a genome for 1 second, your responses will not match those of other 2 miners, and as a result, you will not receive a reward for that. However, the results submitted by these miners actually matched those of the other two miners. I had to take action and blacklist these miners until I talk to them. Blacklisting does not imply cheating until it is proven. The miners managed to get a list of their jobs beforehand from the server and train and have the responses ready beforehand. As soon as Genomaster sends them the new job, they respond with the correct response. This means the work has actually been done but on multiple GPUs. However, since we have stated that multi-GPU training is not yet supported by our miner code, it does not support it. I decided that this is unfair at the current state of the subnet. While I will be working to enforce this on the GenoMaster side, miners involved have changed to run our original miner code.

In the side note, while I strongly appreciate when miners report issues and bugs that we can address, we are all part of the Bittensor ecosystem, and there are subnets older than ours still working on their incentive mechanism issues. I do not appreciate making judgments, jumping to conclusions, and creating chaos in the channel. Decisions on parameter changes in the subnet will be made by the team based on the severity of the problem in the subnet, not via direct messages and pressure from individuals.
